        <p>Here's an example where we have to scale both equations.</p>

        <example>
            <title>Scaling Both Equations</title>
            <statement>
                <p>Solve the system of equations using the elimination method.
                    <md>
                        <mrow>
                            \left\{
                                \begin{alignedat}{4}
                                2x \amp {}+{} \amp  3y \amp {}={} \amp 10 \\
                                -3x \amp {}+{} \amp  5y \amp {}={} \amp {-15}
                                \end{alignedat}
                            \right.
                        </mrow>
                    </md>
                </p>
            </statement>
            <solution>
                <p>Considering the coefficients of <m>x</m> (<m>2</m> and <m>-3</m>) and the coefficients of <m>y</m> (<m>3</m> and <m>5</m>) we see that we cannot eliminate the <m>x</m> or the <m>y</m> variable by scaling a single equation. We will need to scale <em>both</em>.</p>

                <p>The <m>x</m>-terms already have opposite signs, so we choose to eliminate <m>x</m>. The least common multiple of <m>2</m> and <m>3</m> is <m>6</m>. We can scale the first equation by <m>3</m> and the second equation by <m>2</m> so that the equations have terms <m>6x</m> and <m>-6x</m>, which will cancel when added.<md>
                    <mrow>
                        \amp\left\{
                            \begin{alignedat}{4}
                            \multiplyleft{3}(2x\amp {}+{} \amp 3y) \amp {}={}\amp \multiplyleft{3}(10) \\
                            \multiplyleft{2}(-3x\amp {}+{} \amp 5y) \amp {}={}\amp \multiplyleft{2}(-15)
                            \end{alignedat}
                        \right.
                    </mrow>
                    <mrow>
                        \amp\left\{
                            \begin{alignedat}{4}
                            6x\amp {}+{} \amp 9y \amp {}={} \amp 30 \\
                            -6x\amp {}+{} \amp 10y \amp {}={} \amp {-30}
                            \end{alignedat}
                        \right.
                    </mrow>
                </md></p>
                <p>At this point we can add the corresponding sides from the two equations and solve for <m>y</m>:<md>
                    <mrow>\begin{aligned}6x+9y\\{}-6x+10y\end{aligned}\amp=\begin{aligned}30\\{}-30\end{aligned}</mrow>
                    <intertext>So we have:</intertext>
                    <mrow>19y\amp=0</mrow>
                    <mrow>\divideunder{19y}{19}\amp=\divideunder{0}{19}</mrow>
                    <mrow>y\amp=0</mrow>
                </md></p>

                <p>To solve for <m>x</m>, we'll replace <m>y</m> with <m>0</m> in <m>2x+3y=10</m>:
                    <md>
                        <mrow>2x+3y\amp=10</mrow>
                        <mrow>2x+3(\substitute{0})\amp=10</mrow>
                        <mrow>2x\amp=10</mrow>
                        <mrow>x\amp=5</mrow>
                    </md>
                </p>
                <p>We'll check the system using <m>x=5</m> and <m>y=0</m> in each of the original equations:
                    <md>
                        <mrow>2x+3y\amp=10  \amp  -3x+5y\amp=-15</mrow>
                        <mrow>2(\substitute{5})+3(\substitute{0})\amp\stackrel{?}{=}10  \amp  -3(\substitute{5})+5(\substitute{0})\amp\stackrel{?}{=}-15</mrow>
                        <mrow>10+0\amp\stackrel{\checkmark}{=}10  \amp  -15+0\amp\stackrel{\checkmark}{=}-15</mrow>
                    </md>
                So the system's solution is <m>(5,0)</m> and the solution set is <m>\{(5,0)\}</m>.
                </p>
            </solution>
        </example>

